ssessing components, right? I wonder how the user feels about that — if that's something they were aware of. Overall, I should keep this in mind moving forward!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating Gradle dependencies**\\\\n\\\\nI’m exploring how to set up my Gradle configuration using `testImplementation(\\\\\\\"io.quarkus:quarkus-junit-config:$libraryVersion\\\\\\\")`. I need to consider creating a sanitized jar from the original resolved file and replace it in the test classpath. It seems I might need to adjust compile classpath too and think about transitive dependencies when excluding modules. I wonder if excluding the root module would also exclude its transitive dependencies or not. I should organize all these points clearly!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Configuring native-image plugin**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking into how the native-image plugin utilizes `runtimeClasspath`, and I should consider excluding `quarkus-junit-config` this way: \\\\n\\\\n``` \\\\nconfigurations.testRuntimeClasspath {\\\\n  exclude group: 'io.quarkus', module:'quarkus-junit-config'\\\\n} \\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nBut then I wonder about transitive dependencies — they might still come through the `compileClasspath`. Excluding only the module doesn't automatically exclude transitive ones. I might lean toward filtering with `tasks.withType(Test)` to clean up the classpath, ensuring `graalvmNative` is appropriately set up. I should search for examples to confirm my approach!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_8qkrDFBb2kpkrqONRP5Uahcw|fc_083345cb143e1fb40169fbbbf9cb5c819ea4403eeb4e5507f0\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"grep -R \\\"binaries.*test\\\" -n tests/src/*/*/*/build.gradle | head -20 && grep -R \\\"classpath.*graalvmNative\\\\|graalvmNative.*classpath\\\\|runtimeClasspath\\\" -n tests/src | head -50\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {